ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum duration (time) of the JT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the JT interval. The JT interval is defined as the time from the J point (end of ventricular depolarization, the point at which the QRS meets the ST segment) to the end of the T wave (representing the end of ventricular repolarization).

Concepts.definition: The maximum duration (time) of the JT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the JT interval. The JT interval is defined as the time from the J point (end of ventricular depolarization, the point at which the QRS meets the ST segment) to the end of the T wave (representing the end of ventricular repolarization).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave.

Concepts.definition: The maximum duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave.

Concepts.definition: The maximum duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum duration (time) between successive peaks of R waves in a particular set of RR intervals.

Concepts.definition: The maximum duration (time) between successive peaks of R waves in a particular set of RR intervals.

Concepts.longName: Maximum ST Segment Depression by ECG Finding
Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic finding of the maximum depression of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the depression of the ST segment.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum deviation (distance from baseline, positive or negative, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the deviation of the ST segment.

Concepts.definition: The maximum deviation (distance from baseline, positive or negative, usually measured in mm) of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the deviation of the ST segment.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The maximum elevation of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the elevation of the ST segment.

Concepts.definition: The maximum elevation of the ST segment, obtained from a set of measurements of the elevation of the ST segment.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The minimum duration (time) of the JT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the JT interval. The JT interval is defined as the time from the J point (end of ventricular depolarization, the point at which the QRS meets the ST segment) to the end of the T wave (representing the end of ventricular repolarization).

Concepts.definition: The minimum duration (time) of the JT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the JT interval. The JT interval is defined as the time from the J point (end of ventricular depolarization, the point at which the QRS meets the ST segment) to the end of the T wave (representing the end of ventricular repolarization).

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The minimum duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave.

Concepts.definition: The minimum duration (time) of the PR interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the PR interval. The PR interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the P wave (representing the onset of atrial depolarization) to the beginning of the R wave (representing the onset of ventricular depolarization). In some cases, a Q wave will precede the R wave, in which case the PR interval is measured from the beginning of the P wave to the beginning of the Q wave.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The minimum duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave.

Concepts.definition: The minimum duration (time) of the QT interval, obtained from a set of measurements of the QT interval. The QT interval is defined as the time from the beginning of the QRS complex to the end of the T wave, representing the time it takes for the ventricles to depolarize and subsequently repolarize. In some cases, the Q wave will be absent, in which case the QT interval is measured from the beginning of the R wave to the end of the T wave.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: The minimum duration (time) between successive peaks of R waves in a particular set of RR intervals.

Concepts.definition: The minimum duration (time) between successive peaks of R waves in a particular set of RR intervals.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggregate T wave amplitude value based on the measurement of T wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: An aggregate T wave amplitude value based on the measurement of T wave amplitudes from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the T wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the mean amplitude (usually measured in mV) of the T wave measured from the isoelectric baseline to the peak of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. Based on the recording gain, this measurement may also be reported in mm. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggregate T wave area value based on the measurement of T wave areas from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: An aggregate T wave area value based on the measurement of T wave areas from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the area of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the area of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A numerical representation of the electrocardiographic vector assessed at maximum deviation of the T wave from the isoelectric baseline, usually reported for the frontal plane. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: A numerical representation of the electrocardiographic vector assessed at maximum deviation of the T wave from the isoelectric baseline, usually reported for the frontal plane. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggregate T wave duration value based on the measurement of T wave duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: An aggregate T wave duration value based on the measurement of T wave duration intervals from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the T wave to the offset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic interval measured from the onset of the T wave to the offset of the T wave of a single beat utilizing one or more leads. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A statement about an electrocardiographic recording describing technical issues or interference during the recording, processing, or transmission of the data. This does not represent an electrocardiographic diagnosis. (CDISC)

Concepts.definition: A statement about an electrocardiographic recording describing technical issues or interference during the recording, processing, or transmission of the data. This does not represent an electrocardiographic diagnosis. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An aggregate Tpeak-Tend value based on the measurement of Tpeak-Tend from multiple beats within a single ECG. The method of aggregation, which can vary, is typically a measure of central tendency such as the mean. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredName: Acute Myocardial Ischemia by ECG Assessment
ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic finding assessment of new or presumed new significant ST-segment-T wave (ST-T) changes or new left bundle branch block consistent with acute myocardial ischemia. (Thygesen K, Alpert JS, Jaffe AS, et al.: the Writing Group on behalf of the Joint ESC/ACCF/AHA/WHF Task Force for the Universal Definition of Myocardial Infarction. J Am Coll Cardiol 60(16):1-18, 2012)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: A comparative interpretation of an ECG relative to a previous (comparator) ECG. The definition of the comparator ECG may be specified elsewhere. Common comparator result values include improved, no change, deteriorated. (CDISC)

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum number of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during a specified period of time, and usually expressed in beats per minute.

Concepts.definition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum number of atrial depolarizations (P waves) recorded during a specified period of time, and usually expressed in beats per minute.

ValueMeaning.preferredDefinition: An electrocardiographic measurement of the maximum number of depolarisations of a specific region of the heart, most often the ventricles, recorded during a specified, extended period of time, and usually expressed in beats per minute.
